node.text:
Average duration of a human blink: 0.25 seconds.

A lot can happen in the blink of an eye.

Across the universe 15,000 stars will be born and 300 star will explode. 
15,000,000 rogue planets will form. 

The sun will burn 175,000,000 tons of hydrogen and produce 96,100,000,000,000,00,000,000,000 joules of energy.

30 black holes will be born. 

The universe will expand by 527,250 kilometers. 

Our galaxy will travel 250 kilometers and grow by 125 meters. 

The Andromeda galaxy will get 27 kilometers closer and light will travel 74,948 kilometers. 

Approximate number of blinks in a human lifetime: 650,000,000. 

Think next time you blink.

 🌌 My Pages @TheOurDeepSpace & @TheOurEpicNature 🔭

Do you love Universe ❤

Are you ready to explore Space 🔭 @TheOurSpace

Image credit: @melodysheep_

node.title: In the Blink of an Eye: Space in an Instant

node.text:
Are you ready to explore Space 🔭 @theourspace

#planet #planets #galaxy #galaxies #NASA #Spacex #hubble #space #science #scientist #sciences #astronomy #universe #telescope #cosmos #nebula #supernova  #nightsky #blackhole #star #stars #astrology #physics #astronaut #astrophysics #astronomer #elonmusk #nature #milkywaychasers #astrophotography

Wildfires have erupted around the world; the most devastating in Turkey. 😢 Italy, USA, Spain, France, Cyprus, Finland, Lebanon, Canada & Greece have also had terrible fires! There has been severe flooding in Germany, China, Italy, Belgium & Netherlands. Hail bigger than tennis balls has rained down in northern Italy, and it’s even snowed in Brazil!
The second largest river in South America, Paraná River, is currently suffering from a severe drought, and we’ve seen tornadoes in Czechia. 🙏🏽 🌎 😞

Please tag your friends, share this on your stories!

node.text:
How do you say ‘Galaxy’ in your language? 🌌 Andromeda is the closest large galaxy to us! 🌎  At 140,000 light years across, it’s 40% bigger than our 100,000 light year diameter Milky Way. If the whole galaxy were bright enough, this is what you’d see at night (not to perfect scale and with the moon as a reference) My 2nd Page @TheOurDeepSpace Our YouTube Channel. Link in Bio @TheOurSpace

node.text:
Do you remember Comet NEOWISE? One year anniversary of the great comet neowise! Probably the most photographed comet in history. Comets are a great reminder that things in the sky are constantly changing, sometimes slowly but also sometimes quickly. Over the course of a month this comet went from being a small dot visible before sunrise, to a massive bright comet. Here is an image captured of the comet above Seattle from bellevue. The scale of this image is completely true to real life, the comet when properly processed DOES appear this large in the sky. ☄ Which photo is your favorite 1~9? 🔭

node.text:
Yesterday‘s Full Moon 🌕🔥

"The reddish orange color of the Moon soon after the Moon rise is due to the ongoing wildfires that's occurring in the west, mainly in Nevada. I was surprised to see the impact of this reach the east coast and the color in the image was a sort of evidence for this phenomenon. In my own assumptions, the wildfire smoke is diffusing the sun rays coming from the west, which in return are being refracted by the atmosphere, and finally ending on the Moon to project this color while the Moon is still in a low position. As the Moon got higher, the color went back to normal as no further refracted light was projected on it."
 🔭 My Pages @TheOurDeepSpace & @TheOurEpicNature
